Executive Summary

This analysis examines 2,082 restaurants in Dublin to identify optimal opportunities for a new coffee shop. Using TripAdvisor data, we analyzed cuisine preferences, rating distributions, and competitive positioning to inform location strategy.

Data Visualizations

1. Top Cuisine Types in Dublin

Cafes rank #8 with 269 establishments, representing 12.9% of Dublin's restaurant market. Vegetarian-friendly dominates with 727 venues.

2. Rating Distribution Analysis

Over 70% of Dublin establishments achieve 4.0+ ratings, with average rating of 3.99. This indicates high customer expectations.

3. Cafe Performance Analysis

Analysis of cafe ratings reveals that successful cafes consistently maintain 4.5+ ratings with high customer engagement.

4. Price Range vs Rating

Budget, mid-range, and premium establishments show similar rating distributions, suggesting quality execution matters more than price point.

5. Review Volume Distribution

Most establishments have modest review counts, with median around 100 reviews, showing sustained customer engagement is key.

6. Customer Engagement Analysis

The scatter plot reveals the sweet spot: high ratings (4.5+) combined with substantial review volume (200+).

7. Top vs Bottom Performers

Side-by-side comparison shows the stark difference quality makes. Top cafes cluster around 4.5-5.0 ratings.

8. Market Saturation by Quality Tier

The Excellent tier (4.5+) has less competition, suggesting opportunity for quality-focused new entrants.

AI Collaboration Reflection

How AI Helped

  • Writing code faster: AI generated Python scripts for data analysis and visualizations
  • Solving problems: When encountering issues, AI suggested alternative approaches that worked
  • Building the website: Creating this HTML dashboard with clean design and responsive layout
  • Publishing online: Setting up GitHub Pages to make the website live

What I Learned

Being clear helps: When I asked AI "fix my code," I got basic answers. When I explained exactly what error I was seeing and what I wanted to do, I got much better help.

Trying different solutions: My biggest challenge was a bug that kept breaking my charts. After many hours trying to fix it, AI suggested changing where I ran the code. This taught me that sometimes you need to change your approach, not just fix the code.

What AI couldn't do: While AI was great at writing code, it couldn't help me with:

  • Understanding what the data means for a coffee shop business
  • Deciding which findings matter most
  • Knowing about Dublin's cafe market
  • Making business recommendations

Working together: AI is a powerful tool, but not a replacement for thinking. AI helped me code faster and better, but I had to understand the business side, think critically about the data, and decide what the numbers actually mean.

Main Point: AI helped me finish this professional project in 11 hours instead of days. But the real value came from me understanding the data‚Äîrealizing that Dublin cafes can succeed by focusing on quality (4.5+ ratings) in a market that has competition but isn't overcrowded.
